Anonymous Mon 19 Dec 2022 01:07:09 No.53117331 Report
Quoted By: >>53118107 >>53118742 >>53119031
>53098381
>The music isn't what I was expecting either. I know a lot of work went into it. Is it supposed to sound like 1990s college radio station music, but chiptunes? Why the aesthetic choice?
This is pretty on-the-money. I knew that if I made hyper-realistic punk/rock songs like 90% similar to the original, it would be trite. People would just listen from the perspective of the original, prefer the original, and look at mine's small differences as mistakes.
So I changed the genre to something closer to "8 bit rock" because chiptunes are malleable. But most importantly, it would be so unique that people would enjoy the two versions in a completely different way.
I gave the songs new solos, changed the chord progressions, and embellished the melody where I knew it would otherwise be repetitive in the genre. I kept a realistic drum kit but made everything else crunchy, which makes the style really distinct.
And I specifically avoided a lot of punk tunes because they weren't melodic and harmonic enough for the chiptune genre to carry them. Many punk tunes get their spark from the lyrics, overtop these mundane riffs and chord loops. But since retro music doesn't have a speaker, I need to replace all of that musical interest with just basic tones. It's a fun challenge!

if i can give you some suggestions
practice on small things, and sometimes even unrelated things if you feel embarrassed
a sketchbook filled with ugly hands, bottles, mannequins and actual animals feels much more natural than full fledged compositions you're not happy with.
once you reach a point where you're happy with your average results it gets easier: the learning curve even steeper but you'll enjoy the process more.
